This paper deals with the Traveling Salesman Problem, which is a classic problem in computer science and falls under the category of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The paper specifically focuses on the approximation ratio of the greedy algorithm for the problem, which involves analyzing the structure of the problem instance and its solution space, making it relevant to computational geometry (cs.CG). The paper also involves analyzing the performance of heuristics, which is a common topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing the performance of algorithms on different types of instances, such as Euclidean and rectilinear instances, which are common in machine learning and optimization (cs.LG) and numerical analysis (cs.NA), respectively.
